**A coffee plantation is usually designed in a separate area, surrounded by a fence or wall to protect the plants from wildlife and the elements. Coffee gardens are often divided into many different areas, serving different stages of the growing and caring process. The conventional coffee growing area is the area where the seeds are sown in the ground and then wait until they close the yard. After the tree matures and begins to bear fruit, the harvesting area will be used to harvest the coffee. Regular rows of coffee trees are built in horizontal and vertical rows, creating a tighter network of coffee trees. These rows of coffee trees are often protected by water beam systems to ensure that the trees are always fully watered. In addition, coffee orchards may have gaps between rows of trees, which are used to grow different plants such as vegetables, flowers, or side crops. Coffee gardens are often very well cared for, including pruning, spraying and periodic fertilization. When the coffee cherries are ripe, the harvest workers will be summoned to pick the cherries from the trees. This process is usually done by hand, as the resulting coffee needs to be picked at the right time to ensure the quality of the final product** - <@1079236530591252512> (fast)
